'''Timothy Bruce Fayulu''' (born 24 July 1999) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Armenian Premier League]] club [[FC Noah]] on loan from [[FC Sion|Sion]]. Born in Switzerland, he plays for the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]].

==Club career==
Fayulu began his footballing career as a forward with CS Italien when he was 7 years old. Switching to goalkeeper after a growth spurt, he spent his early career with various youth clubs in Switzerland before moving to [[FC Sion|Sion]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://olympique-geneve.ch/parcours-un-petit-gardien-de-1-metre-91/|title=Parcours d'un petit gardien de 1 mètre 91|date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Fayulu made his professional debut for the Swiss club in a 3–0 [[Swiss Super League]] win over [[Grasshopper Club Zürich|Grasshopper]] on 22 May 2019.

Often used as a second-choice goalkeeper in the earliest stages of his career, the first choice being [[Kevin Fickentscher]], during the [[2020–21 Swiss Super League|2020–21 season]] he started featuring for Sion more regularly, in alternative to the same team-mate. He started the 2021–22 season as the starter at Sion, before soon losing the starting spot to Fickentscher once again.

On 24 June 2022, Fayulu moved on a season-long loan to [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Winterthur|url=https://fcwinterthur.ch/news/timothy-fayulu-neuer-torhueter/|title=Timothy Fayulu neuer Torhüter|date=24 June 2022|access-date=28 June 2022|language=de}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in Switzerland, Fayulu is of Congolese descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiookapi.net/2015/10/02/actualite/sport/foot-amical-u18-18-leopards-retenus-contre-langleterre|title=Foot-amical (U18): 18 Léopards retenus contre l'Angleterre|date=October 2, 2015|website=Radio Okapi}}</ref> He represented the [[DR Congo national under-20 football team|DR Congo U18]] side in a friendly 8–0 loss to the [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]] in October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Association|first=The Football|title=England U17s hit eight in World Cup warm-up with DR Congo|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2015/oct/07/england-u17s-v-congo-dr-st-georges-park-match-report-071015|access-date=2021-03-16|website=thefa.com|language=en}}</ref>

In March 2021, he received his first call-up both from the [[DR Congo national football team|Congolese senior national team]] (for two [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] matches)<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-03-10|title=Elim-CAN 2021: les 31 de Nsengi Biembe pour le Gabon et la Gambie avec Mbokani, Masasi, Lilepo, Inonga et Bwalya|url=https://actualite.cd/index.php/2021/03/10/elim-can-2021-les-31-de-nsengi-biembe-pour-le-gabon-et-la-gambie-avec-mbokani-masasi|access-date=2021-03-16|website=Actualite.cd|language=fr}}</ref> and the [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Swiss under-21 national team]]: he chose the latter side, thus being selected in the squad that would take part in the [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] in [[Hungary]] and [[Slovenia]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Baumgartner|first=Stefan|title=Mauro Lustrinelli annonce sa sélection pour l'EURO M21|url=https://www.football.ch/fr/asf/equipes-nationales/m21/news/mauro-lustrinelli-annonce-sa-s%C3%A9lection-pour-l-euro-m21.aspx|access-date=2021-03-16|website=www.football.ch|language=fr}}</ref> He debuted with the senior DR Congo national team in a friendly 3–1 win over [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] on 8 June 2025.<ref>https://africasoccer.com/fc-basel-eyes-congolese-international-timothy-fayulu-as-future-no-1/</ref>

On 16 November 2025, in the final of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|second round of 2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]], DR Congo had tied [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] 1–1, taking the game to penalties. Fayulu, who had been substituted on in the 89th minute, saved a penalty from [[Semi Ajayi]] which, after a successful penalty from [[Chancel Mbemba]], secured DR Congo's qualification for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-offs]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stevens |first=Rob |date=2025-11-16 |title=African World Cup 2026 play-off: DR Congo beat Nigeria on penalties |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c0rpj9jkz45o |access-date=2025-11-23 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> After the match, in an interview with [[FIFA]], he stated "It would be my ultimate dream to be able to wear my country's shirt at the World Cup."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Fayulu: I'm always ready for Congo DR |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/timothy-fayulu-congo-dr-interview |access-date=2025-11-23 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref>

